Comparing Deep Learning Approaches for Glaucoma Detection¶

Deep Learning Final Project¶

Glaucoma is a group of progressive eye diseases characterized by the degeneration of retinal cells and their axons leading to irreversable vision loss. Glaucoma affects over 76 million people globally and has significant challenges to normal detection. A major challenge in glaucoma is that this disease can progress over time silently (or at least minimal symptoms) until vision loss has started to occur. Like most other diseases early detection is critical to slowing disease progression.

Detection of glaucoma involves multimodal assessments combining fundus imaging, tonometry, pachymetry, and visual field testing. However, manual assessment can be subjective and labor intensive which highlights the need for some automated reliable models. Structural changes suggesing disease progression can include cup to disc ratio (CDR) which is a measure of asymmetry between the eyes, neuroretinal rim thinning, peripapillary atrophy or disc hemorrhages etc.

Clinical data as well can be useful in diagnosis highlighting potential irregular values for risk factors. Some typical risk factors include elevated intraocular pressure (IOP), but can also include things such as optic disc cupping, pachymtetry (corneal thickness), axial length of the eye, and visual field mean deivation which comes from visual field testing. These clinical values can come from the imaging themselves or separate risk factors when combined with standard information such as age/gender etc.

Recent advances in machine learning and artificial intelligence have come up with models that look at imaging and have looked at clinical data. However, not much has been done on mixing the 2 approaches to overlay clinical data with the imaging to take a combination approach. Thus, the project here uses 2 different neural networks :

  1. A convolutional neural network (CNN) that will analyze the fundus images and extract features
  2. A feed forward neural network (FNN) that will process the clinical data

By merging these 2 modalities into a predictive model, we aim to improve diagnostic performance compared to image only or clinical information only approaches. The final model will be assessed on typical machine learning metrics of accuracy, AUC/ROC, and confusion matrix metrics.

The data acquired for this project was taken from the PAPILA dataset which was published in 2022 by Kovalyk et al in Nature Scientific Data (https://www.nature.com/articles/s41597-022-01388-1). The downloaded data was obtained from here : https://figshare.com/articles/dataset/PAPILA/14798004?file=35013982. The specific publication here was a simple ResNet50 image classification task, but our work here will attempt to combine the clinical variables to create a multimodal classification system.

Step 1 - Loading in the data¶

Load in the data that was downloaded and do some cleanup.

We will note that there was some imputation that needed to be performed for missing data. In this regard, we choose to take the mean value for the missing data. We could not ignore those data otherwise the sample numbers would be insufficient for a proper model.

We will define the columns once we see the data frame in it's final form below.

import pandas as pd
import os
from glob import glob

# Paths
root_dir = r'C:\Users\derek\Downloads\PAPILA\PAPILA'
fundus_dir = os.path.join(root_dir, 'FundusImages')
clinical_dir = os.path.join(root_dir, 'ClinicalData')
output_metadata_path = os.path.join(root_dir, 'metadata.csv')

# Step 1: Load and clean clinical data
od = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(clinical_dir, 'patient_data_od.txt'), delimiter='\t')
os_ = pd.read_csv(os.path.join(clinical_dir, 'patient_data_os.txt'), delimiter='\t')

# Clean patient IDs: remove '#' only
od['patient_id'] = od.iloc[:, 0].str.replace('#', '')
os_['patient_id'] = os_.iloc[:, 0].str.replace('#', '')

# Drop the original ID column (the first column)
od = od.drop(columns=od.columns[0])
os_ = os_.drop(columns=os_.columns[0])

# Add suffixes to clinical features
od = od.add_suffix('_OD')
os_ = os_.add_suffix('_OS')

# Fix patient_id column names for merging
od = od.rename(columns={'patient_id_OD': 'patient_id'})
os_ = os_.rename(columns={'patient_id_OS': 'patient_id'})

# Merge OD and OS clinical tables
clinical = pd.merge(od, os_, on='patient_id', how='inner')

# Step 2: Process fundus images
image_files = glob(os.path.join(fundus_dir, '*.jpg'))

# Build patient_id to image path dictionary
image_dict = {}
for img_path in image_files:
    fname = os.path.basename(img_path)  # Example: RET001OD.jpg
    patient_id = fname[3:6]              # Extract '001', '002', etc.
    eye = fname[6:8]                     # 'OD' or 'OS'

    if patient_id not in image_dict:
        image_dict[patient_id] = {}
    
    image_dict[patient_id][eye] = img_path

# Convert to DataFrame
image_records = []
for pid, eyes in image_dict.items():
    record = {
        'patient_id': pid,
        'right_eye_image_path': eyes.get('OD', None),
        'left_eye_image_path': eyes.get('OS', None),
    }
    image_records.append(record)

images_df = pd.DataFrame(image_records)

Now that we have the data into data frames let's pause here and make sure that we make sense of what the data columns mean.

First, note there are suffixes on a few of the column names consisting of OS and OD. OD stands for occulus dexter which refers to the right eye, and OS stands for occuls sinister which refers to the left eye. It is possible for glaucoma to develop in one eye first and not the other for many years. This is called unilateral glaucoma and is actually quite common. For this reason we need to make sure that we keep the eye designations and their associated features distinct.

Label in this case we have made as the glaucoma designation. Here I have decided to consider a patient-level approach to the data and consider anyone that has glaucoma symptoms in either eye as a glaucoma patient.

That being said let's define the individual columns :

patient_id : patient ID given in the external data set. They have "#" values in the download which we will need to do some text manipulation on. age : The patient's age

gender : Gender of the patient. 0 = Male, 1 = Female

Diagnosis : Glaucoma diagnosis. 0 = No glaucoma, 1 = glaucoma, 2 = suspected glaucoma. Suspected glaucoma isn't definite and could be problematic in the model.

dioptre : measurement of the eye's refractive power units in diopters (D).

astigmatism : degree of irregular curvature of the cornea or lens.

phakic/pseudophakic : 0 = natural lens present, 1 = artificial introcular lens implanted (after cataract surgery)

pneumatic : Intraocular pressure (IOP) measured during a pneumatic tonometer (air puff test)

perkins : Intraocular pressure (IOP) measured during a perkins applanation tonometer (portable test)

pachymetry : Thickness of the cornea measured in micrometers (um)

axial length : Distance from the front (cornea) to the back (retina) of the eye measured in milimeters (mm).

VF_MD : Visual field mean deviation (mesured in dB).

# datasets.py

import torch
from torch.utils.data import Dataset
import pandas as pd
from PIL import Image
import torchvision.transforms as transforms

class PAPILADataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, csv_file, img_size=224):
        self.data = pd.read_csv(csv_file)
        
        # Clinical features (all columns except images and label)
        self.clinical_features = [col for col in self.data.columns if ('_OD' in col or '_OS' in col)]
        
        self.transform = transforms.Compose([
            transforms.Resize((img_size, img_size)),
            transforms.ToTensor(),   # Converts image to [0,1] and CHW format
        ])
        
    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.data)
    
    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        row = self.data.iloc[idx]
        
        # Load left and right eye images
        left_img = Image.open(row['left_eye_image_path']).convert('RGB')
        right_img = Image.open(row['right_eye_image_path']).convert('RGB')
        
        left_img = self.transform(left_img)
        right_img = self.transform(right_img)
        
        # Load clinical features
        clinical = torch.tensor(row[self.clinical_features].values, dtype=torch.float32)
        
        # Load label
        label = torch.tensor(row['label'], dtype=torch.float32)
        
        return left_img, right_img, clinical, label

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
from PIL import Image

# Set paths
metadata_path = r'C:\Users\derek\Downloads\PAPILA\PAPILA\metadata.csv'

# Load metadata
df = pd.read_csv(metadata_path)
print(f"Shape of metadata: {df.shape}")

# --- 1. Class balance ---
plt.figure(figsize=(5,5))
df['label'].value_counts().plot(kind='pie', autopct='%1.1f%%', labels=['Non-Glaucoma', 'Glaucoma'], colors=['skyblue', 'salmon'])
plt.title('Class Balance (Glaucoma vs Non-Glaucoma)')
plt.show()

plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
sns.countplot(x='label', data=df, palette='Set2')
plt.title('Class Distribution')
plt.xticks([0, 1], ['Non-Glaucoma', 'Glaucoma'])
plt.show()

# --- 2. Clinical Features: Histograms and Boxplots ---

clinical_features = [
    'Age_OD', 'Age_OS',
    'Pneumatic_OD', 'Pneumatic_OS',
    'Perkins_OD', 'Perkins_OS',
    'Pachymetry_OD', 'Pachymetry_OS',
    'Axial_Length_OD', 'Axial_Length_OS'
]

# Histograms
for feature in clinical_features:
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    sns.histplot(df[feature], kde=True, bins=30, color='teal')
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {feature}')
    if 'Age' in feature:
        plt.xlim(20, 100)
    elif 'Pachymetry' in feature:
        plt.xlim(400, 700)
    elif 'Axial_Length' in feature:
        plt.xlim(20, 30)
    plt.xlabel(feature)
    plt.show()

# Boxplots (separated by label)
for feature in clinical_features:
    plt.figure(figsize=(6,4))
    sns.boxplot(x='label', y=feature, data=df, palette='Set3')
    plt.title(f'{feature} by Glaucoma Label')
    plt.xticks([0, 1], ['Non-Glaucoma', 'Glaucoma'])
    plt.show()

# --- 3. Correlation Heatmap ---

# Only numeric columns

def show_patient_images(patient_row, title):
    left_img = Image.open(patient_row['left_eye_image_path'])
    right_img = Image.open(patient_row['right_eye_image_path'])
    
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize=(8,4))
    axes[0].imshow(left_img)
    axes[0].set_title('Left Eye')
    axes[0].axis('off')
    
    axes[1].imshow(right_img)
    axes[1].set_title('Right Eye')
    axes[1].axis('off')
    
    plt.suptitle(title)
    plt.show()

# Display normal examples
print("Normal Patients:")
for idx, row in normal_patients.iterrows():
    show_patient_images(row, f"Patient ID {row['patient_id']} (Normal)")

# Display glaucoma examples
print("Glaucoma Patients:")
for idx, row in glaucoma_patients.iterrows():
    show_patient_images(row, f"Patient ID {row['patient_id']} (Glaucoma)")

There is a lot to unpack here so let's just do some general observations.

First, we have some pretty severe imbalance in the groups. We have many more non-glaucoma patients than those with. This could be problematic later when trying to classify into each group.

Second, the age of the patients in the glaucoma group appear to be significantly higher than those non-glaucoma patients. This isn't a huge surprise sinece glaucoma tends to be more prevalent in the population at later years, but scientificially we would want this to be nearly the same.

Third, there are normal distributions on pneumatic, perkins, pachymetry . There is a slight skewness to the axial length with a few outliers.

Fourth, when comparing the box and whisker plots between glaucoma and non-glaucoma there doesn't appear to be much difference between many of the clinical features. This lends to the central hypothesis that a visual inspection of the fundus images would be more appropriate to make a clinical diagnosis of glaucoma rather than just by clinical features.

Fifth, we performed a simple correlation analysis to show that there isn't much correlation between the values. This makes sense due to the heterogenous nature of the disase and that not all clinical variables will scale the same way. In other words, disease state is different for everyone.

Lastly, we just showed a few of the fundus images such that we can see what we are working with.

    avg = None
    count = 0
    for path in paths:

        if avg is None:
            avg = img

Model that only looks at clinical data and nothing else.¶

The first model we want to implement is a model that only looks at the clinical data and ignores the fundus images.

We have developed a very simple and shallow feedforward neural network (multilayer perceptron) with an input layer, 2 hidden layers with ReLU activation, and an output layer.

The simplicity of the model is valid here since we are only working with a handful of clinical variables and is perfect for structured tabular data. Additionally, there is a very low risk of overfitting with such a model. Additional benefits include, speed of training and scalability to additional features later if necessary.

Also, it pairs well with pytorch BCE loss function since it outputs a logit value per patient.

So let's now go on with defining and running the model.

class ClinicalOnlyGlaucomaModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_clinical_features):
        super(ClinicalOnlyGlaucomaModel, self).__init__()
        
        self.mlp = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(num_clinical_features, 128),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(128, 64),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(64, 1)   # No Sigmoid
        )
        
    def forward(self, clinical_data):
        output = self.mlp(clinical_data)  # (batch_size, 1)
        return output

from torch.utils.data import Dataset, DataLoader, random_split
import torch.optim as optim


class ClinicalDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, csv_file):
        self.data = pd.read_csv(csv_file)
        self.clinical_features = [col for col in self.data.columns if ('_OD' in col or '_OS' in col)]
        
    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.data)
    
    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        row = self.data.iloc[idx]
    
        # Force all clinical feature values to float32
        clinical_values = row[self.clinical_features].astype(np.float32).values
    
        clinical = torch.tensor(clinical_values, dtype=torch.float32)
        label = torch.tensor(row['label'], dtype=torch.float32)
    
        return clinical, label

from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score, accuracy_score

train_losses = []
val_losses = []
val_accuracies = []
val_aucs = []

for epoch in range(num_epochs):
    model.train()
    running_loss = 0.0
    for clinical_data, labels in train_loader:
        clinical_data = clinical_data.to(device)
        labels = labels.to(device)
        labels = labels.unsqueeze(1)  # Make labels (batch_size, 1)

        optimizer.zero_grad()
        outputs = model(clinical_data)  # outputs shape (batch_size, 1)
        
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        
        running_loss += loss.item()
    
    avg_train_loss = running_loss / len(train_loader)
    train_losses.append(avg_train_loss)
    
    # Validation phase
    model.eval()
    val_loss = 0.0
    all_labels = []
    all_preds = []
    with torch.no_grad():
        for clinical_data, labels in val_loader:
            clinical_data = clinical_data.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)
            labels = labels.unsqueeze(1)  # Again make labels (batch_size, 1)
            
            outputs = model(clinical_data)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            val_loss += loss.item()
            
            preds = torch.sigmoid(outputs)  # Since model outputs raw logits
            preds = preds.detach().cpu().numpy()
            labels = labels.detach().cpu().numpy()
            
            all_labels.extend(labels.flatten())
            all_preds.extend(preds.flatten())
    
    avg_val_loss = val_loss / len(val_loader)
    val_losses.append(avg_val_loss)
    
    val_acc = accuracy_score(np.round(all_labels), np.round(all_preds))
    val_auc = roc_auc_score(all_labels, all_preds)
    
    val_accuracies.append(val_acc)
    val_aucs.append(val_auc)
    
    print(f"Epoch [{epoch+1}/{num_epochs}] "
          f"Train Loss: {avg_train_loss:.4f} "
          f"Val Loss: {avg_val_loss:.4f} "
          f"Val Acc: {val_acc:.4f} "
          f"Val AUC: {val_auc:.4f}")

Fundus Imaging ONLY analysis¶

Now that we have a proper baseline for the clinical data, let's get a baseline for a model that only looks at the images.

The model architecture that I've selected here is a convolutional neural network (CNN) based on a pretrained ResNet18. The ResNet18 comes from torchvision.models. Each eye image is passed through the ResNet encoder producing a 512 dimensional feature (recall we resized teh images to 512x512 since we don't lose much information) vector per eye. The fusion layer is where the 2 512D vectors are concatenated creating a 1024D feature. The classifier is a single neuron with fully connected layers that reduces the dimesion from 1024 to 128 and has a logit output. The activation used is BCEWightLogitsLoss which handles sigmoid and loss internally.

The reason why I've selected Resnet18 is that it is widely used in opthamaology classification tasks with retinal, optic and fundus imaging in other studies and performs very well on smaller datasets. Staring with the ImageNet pretrained weights will help with the transfer learning for low-level features such as edges and textures which is useful since we have only a couple hundred patients. Additionally, the Resnet18 architecture is that it is efficient and fast even on CPU (which is all I have right now to work on).

The classifier node is linear (1024->128) and combines fused features from both eyes. A ReLU is used for non-linearity and a linear output is used for (128 -> 1) such that the final output is logit.

Now that the definitions have been done, let's implement the Resnet18 architecture and perform model fitting and evaluation.

class FundusDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, csv_file, img_size=224):
        self.data = pd.read_csv(csv_file)
        self.transform = transforms.Compose([
            transforms.Resize((img_size, img_size)),
            transforms.ToTensor(),
            transforms.Normalize([0.5], [0.5])  # Simple normalization
        ])
        
    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.data)
    
    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        row = self.data.iloc[idx]
        
        left_img = Image.open(row['left_eye_image_path']).convert('RGB')
        right_img = Image.open(row['right_eye_image_path']).convert('RGB')
        
        left_img = self.transform(left_img)
        right_img = self.transform(right_img)
        
        label = torch.tensor(row['label'], dtype=torch.float32)
        
        return left_img, right_img, label

class FundusOnlyGlaucomaModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, pretrained=True):
        super(FundusOnlyGlaucomaModel, self).__init__()
        
        base_cnn = models.resnet18(pretrained=pretrained)
        self.cnn_encoder = nn.Sequential(*list(base_cnn.children())[:-1])  # Remove final FC
        
        cnn_output_size = base_cnn.fc.in_features  # 512
        
        self.classifier = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(cnn_output_size * 2, 128),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(128, 1)  # 1 output neuron (raw logits)
        )
        
    def forward(self, left_img, right_img):
        left_feat = self.cnn_encoder(left_img).flatten(1)
        right_feat = self.cnn_encoder(right_img).flatten(1)
        
        fused = torch.cat([left_feat, right_feat], dim=1)  # (batch_size, 1024)
        output = self.classifier(fused)  # (batch_size, 1)
        return output

Multimodal model¶

Finally, let's look at the multimodal data with the clinical data and the imaging data combined into a single model.

Here I have implemented a dual branch deep neural network which fuses the CNN model from the imaging analysis with the MLP of the clinical data model. The CNN branch takes the 2 fundus images and pass it through a shared ResNet18 encoder and outputs a 512D feature per eye (or 1024D total). The clinical feature branch uses the MLP with 2 layers and a ReLU activation outputting a 64D vector. The fusion layer here concatenates the 1024D vector and the 64D clinical vector into a 1088D fused feature. This feature encapsulates a single patient, but has the characteristics of both the fundus image as well as the clinical diagnostics. The classifier head here is a fully connected layers that moves from 1088 -> 128 -> 1 and outputs a binar classification using BCEWithLogitsLoss.

The goal of this model is to mimic clinical decision making by using multiple decision points including fundus imaging and patient history. The fusion model is simple yet effective which just a simple concatenation of the dimensions which represents the merging of imaging and clinical features into a per patient feature set. This can then be shared for further analysis very easily. Each of the models can be extended or replaced at this level very easily for future extension or modification.

So that being said let's create the multimodal model.

class MultimodalDataset(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, csv_file, img_size=224):
        self.data = pd.read_csv(csv_file)
        self.clinical_features = [col for col in self.data.columns if ('_OD' in col or '_OS' in col)]
        self.transform = transforms.Compose([
            transforms.Resize((img_size, img_size)),
            transforms.ToTensor(),
            transforms.Normalize([0.5], [0.5])
        ])
        
    def __len__(self):
        return len(self.data)
    
    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        row = self.data.iloc[idx]
        
        left_img = Image.open(row['left_eye_image_path']).convert('RGB')
        right_img = Image.open(row['right_eye_image_path']).convert('RGB')
        
        left_img = self.transform(left_img)
        right_img = self.transform(right_img)
        
        clinical = torch.tensor(row[self.clinical_features].astype(np.float32).values, dtype=torch.float32)
        label = torch.tensor(row['label'], dtype=torch.float32)
        
        return left_img, right_img, clinical, label

class MultimodalGlaucomaModel(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, num_clinical_features, pretrained=True):
        super(MultimodalGlaucomaModel, self).__init__()
        
        # CNN for fundus images
        base_cnn = models.resnet18(pretrained=pretrained)
        self.cnn_encoder = nn.Sequential(*list(base_cnn.children())[:-1])  # Remove last FC
        
        cnn_output_size = base_cnn.fc.in_features  # 512
        
        # MLP for clinical data
        self.mlp = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(num_clinical_features, 128),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(128, 64),
            nn.ReLU()
        )
        
        # Final classifier
        self.classifier = nn.Sequential(
            nn.Linear(cnn_output_size*2 + 64, 128),
            nn.ReLU(),
            nn.Linear(128, 1)  # 1 output neuron
        )
        
    def forward(self, left_img, right_img, clinical_data):
        left_feat = self.cnn_encoder(left_img).flatten(1)
        right_feat = self.cnn_encoder(right_img).flatten(1)
        
        clinical_feat = self.mlp(clinical_data)
        
        fused = torch.cat([left_feat, right_feat, clinical_feat], dim=1)
        output = self.classifier(fused)
        
        return output

        optimizer.zero_grad()
        outputs = model(left_img, right_img, clinical_data)
        
        loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
        loss.backward()
        optimizer.step()
        
        running_loss += loss.item()
    
    avg_train_loss = running_loss / len(train_loader)
    train_losses.append(avg_train_loss)
    
    # Validation
    model.eval()
    val_loss = 0.0
    all_labels = []
    all_preds = []
    
    with torch.no_grad():
        for left_img, right_img, clinical_data, labels in val_loader:
            left_img = left_img.to(device)
            right_img = right_img.to(device)
            clinical_data = clinical_data.to(device)
            labels = labels.to(device)
            labels = labels.unsqueeze(1)

            outputs = model(left_img, right_img, clinical_data)
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)
            val_loss += loss.item()

            preds = torch.sigmoid(outputs)
            preds = preds.detach().cpu().numpy()
            labels = labels.detach().cpu().numpy()

            all_labels.extend(labels.flatten())
            all_preds.extend(preds.flatten())
    
    avg_val_loss = val_loss / len(val_loader)
    val_losses.append(avg_val_loss)

    val_acc = accuracy_score(np.round(all_labels), np.round(all_preds))
    val_auc = roc_auc_score(all_labels, all_preds)
    
    val_accuracies.append(val_acc)
    val_aucs.append(val_auc)
    
    print(f"Epoch [{epoch+1}/{num_epochs}] "
          f"Train Loss: {avg_train_loss:.4f} "
          f"Val Loss: {avg_val_loss:.4f} "
          f"Val Acc: {val_acc:.4f} "
          f"Val AUC: {val_auc:.4f}")

Well we did some improvment since the AUC went from 0.77 to 0.81. It's not quite at the level of the other models however and not a huge disappointment, but it's not something that we would want to impelement on a wide scale just yet.

Conclusions¶

We have developed 3 different models here based on the data at hand. We deveveloped a multilayered perceptron on the clincial data, a convolutional neural network on the imaging data, and a fusion model taking both of the data sources.

In terms of AUC, the imaging study did the best followed by the clinical only model and finally the fusion model performed the worst. The AUC for imaging was 0.94, clinical data only 0.84, and fusion was 0.81. I think the real take home message here is that there is no single model that comes up with something that we can confidently put inside a clinic yet for diagnostics.

Further directions, get MORE MORE MORE data. We are severely limited here by the amount of data that we have in just a couple of hundred patients. There are larger datasets out there, but they are not for public use yet.

Try different more complicated models. We could try to use some ensemble methods instead of just a simple fusion of features. By doing this we can weight the data differently. One of the considerations of our model is that we treat clinical data and imaging the same. We might want to redo the model with a heavy weight placed on the imaging and using the clinical data with a reduced impact.

Overall, there are many directions to take this type of multimodal approach. A multimodal approach might be beneficial to cancer diagnosis combining tissue pathology with biomaker data, or Alzheimer's diagnosis combining MRI with cognitive testing. Here we are trying to use clinical features with imaging which seems to be a bit lacking. However, the models do perform well overall and are in line with publicly available models.
